[Result ""]
[Auction "E"]
1S pass 2S pass 4S pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 3, chOption: E, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:1, nBasis: 2, nRot: 3, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "7ce83dc2022a3d24890426c3fde360f59476c088cf0d5869153f463354dc66f5"]
[Category "Defense"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "defense/second_hand_play"]
[Student "W"]
{[showcards S:S4]

You are South. The bidding has been as shown.

You lead the \HJ, covered by dummy's \HQ and won by North's \HK. North wins the \HA at the second trick and continues with a small \H ruffed by East.

East then plays the \S4 from his hand. Do you play low? or play the \SJ to force dummy's \SA?

Play the \S3.

If East decides to finesse the \ST then you will still win the one \S trick which you are entitled to win. 

However, with East holding the \SQ it would be very logical for him to go up with the \SA then lead back toward his \SQ, playing North for the \SK. If he plays this way you will get two tricks and defeat the contract.}
[Play "W"]HJ

